<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920102-0140</DOCNO><DOCID>920102-0140.</DOCID><HL>   Landmark Bancorp   Creates Loss Reserve   Totaling $3.2 Million</HL><DATE>01/02/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 4</SO><CO>   LMBC</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)WESTERN U.S. BANKS (BAW)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)INSURANCE (INS)</IN><NS>FINANCING AGREEMENTS (FNC)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LA HABRA, Calif. -- Landmark Bancorp said it would setaside a $3.2 million reserve to cover possible losses fromallegedly unauthorized loans made by a loan officer at itsLandmark Bank unit.   The officer, whose identity wasn't disclosed, approvedsome $4.5 million in loans to several small SouthernCalifornia manufacturers without getting the bank'spermission, and engaged in &quot;other irregular loan activities,&quot;said Craig D. Collette, president and chief executive officerof the bank holding company.</LP><TEXT>   Specific losses to the bank, if any, haven't beendetermined yet and will &quot;depend on the creditworthiness ofthe borrowers&quot; and collateral for the loans, the parentcompany said in a news release. &quot;A preliminary review basedupon the bank's investigation indicates that . . . only aportion appear to possess some degree of risk,&quot; the companysaid.   Landmark Bancorp said its insurance policy may cover allor part of any loss resulting from the alleged wrongdoing,which was first discovered last month during a routine reviewof checks and balances. The loan officer has been fired.   &quot;We don't know the particulars as to how the loans wereinitiated, and we're still looking at that,&quot; Mr. Collettesaid. &quot;The problem was that they weren't approved, and werehidden in the accounting of the bank,&quot; he added. Mr. Collettesaid that the company is continuing to investigate the matterand has contacted federal and state law enforcementauthorities.   The holding company's financial results for 1991 will berevised to reflect the loan loss reserve, he said. &quot;We'llstill show a small profit for the year,&quot; Mr. Collette said,but declined to elaborate.   Landmark said it has $245 million in assets and $224million in deposits. After adjustment for the reserve, thecompany said it will report $165 million in loans and acapital addition of $17.7 million.</TEXT></DOC>